Bummer, this seemed like a good solution, when the `<Root>` component also needs access to the state that's provided.

The reason why this is needed in the first place: I created a component that shows data from a 3rd party data source. The component can be configured (e.g. endpoints) with props by the consumer, so there are a lot of props that need to be used through-out the component tree (<Root>, the table component, search bar, etc.)

I often read that you should define `refs` in the root of the file, rather than in the `useXYZ` function. But since my consuming App can have multiple instances of my component (even nested), the state would be global over all instances, not just the component tree.

```ts
// useXYZ.ts - new state each time I call useXYZ
export function useXYZ () {
  const state = ref(0)
  return { state }
}
// useXYZ.ts - global state for all instances
const state = ref(0)
export function useXYZ () {
  return { state }
}
```

Is there an official way to do this? `provide/inject` is the only thing that comes to mind, but the providers also relies on the data. The only way I can think of is 2 separate functions: one for initialization/providing and one for usage/injection.

